Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @pak choi{1}(trimmed and thinly sliced widthways). Trim and halve the @green beans{80%g}(trimmed and halved).

Zest and halve the @lime{1}(zested and halved).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on high heat. Drain the @king prawns{150%g}(drained).

Once hot, add the @sliced mushrooms{120%g} to the saucepan and fry, stirring occasionally, until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Halfway through cooking the mushrooms, add the prawns to the saucepan and fry for the remaining time, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and utensils after handling raw prawns.

Stir the @red Thai style paste{75%g}, @Thai style spice mix{1%sachet} (add less if you'd prefer things milder) and garlic into the mushrooms.

Stir fry for ~{1%minute}.

Pour the @coconut milk{180%ml}, @soy sauce{25%ml}, @sugar{1%tsp} and @water for the soup{200%ml} into the saucepan.

Bring to the boil, then add the green beans and the pak choi. Simmer until just tender, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Cook so the prawns are opaque in the middle.

Add the @udon noodles{220%g} to the soup and cook, using a #fork{} to gently separate them, until warmed through, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Remove the saucepan from the heat. Stir in the lime zest and half the lime juice.

Taste the soup and add more salt, pepper, lime juice and sugar if needed.

Share the udon noodle soup between your #bowls{}.

Cut any remaining lime into wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!